  "chunk_index": 30,
  "summary": "Following a telephone call from Lily, Alexander Bonaparte Cast reflects on whether she knows about the approaching detective inspector. Concerned that Mrs. Marbury might witness his reaction, he decides to leave his house.\n\nAt Scotland Yard, a meeting is held between the Assistant Commissioner of Police, Inspector Crumb, Hercule Poirot, and the narrator. Inspector Crumb reports on the investigation into Cast, a door-to-door sock salesman. Crumb notes that Cast's movements through Pitt, Bexhill, and Ashford coincide with the locations of the crimes, and that the socks Cast sells are identical to those belonging to Miss Drew. A search of Cast's home revealed a large quantity of socks, note paper, and boxes containing eight new ABC train timetables. Most significantly, Crumb discovered a knife with dried blood hidden behind a coat rack in the hall.\n\nWhile the Assistant Commissioner expresses confidence in catching the murderer, Poirot questions the motive. Inspector Crumb suggests the killer may suffer from an inferiority complex or paranoid delusions. Poirot argues that the selection of victims, such as Betty Barnard, was not accidental but premeditated, suggesting the killer scouted locations and habits in advance. This observation causes Donald Fraser visible anguish.\n\nMeanwhile, Cast stands near a fruit and vegetable shop, feeling hungry, dizzy, and out of money. He sees a poster for the \"ABC Murder Case\" featuring an interview with Poirot and mutters to himself, wondering if Poirot knows his secrets, before continuing to walk.",
